ttractive, articulate, and capable—yet ex-offenders received less than half the callbacks of the equally qualified applicants without criminal backgrounds. Young black men, meanwhile, paid a particularly high price: those with clean records fared no better in their job searches than white men just out of prison. Such shocking barriers to legitimate work, Pager contends, are an important reason that many ex-prisoners soon find themselves back in the realm of poverty, underground employment, and crime that led them to prison in the first place. “Using scholarly research, field research in Milwaukee, and graphics, [Pager] shows that ex-offenders, white or black, stand a very poor chance of getting a legitimate job. . . . Both informative and convincing.”—Library Journal “Marked is that rare book: a penetrating text that rings with moral concern couched in vivid prose—and one of the most useful sociological studies in years.”—Michael Eric Dyson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxEmployment. 0aEx-convictsxEmploymentzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aprison, jailtime, conviction, labor, parole, probation, employment, stigma, recidivism, race, crime, legal system, stereotypes, fear, poverty, skills, training, rehabilitation, reentering society, felon, mass incarceration, racism, sociology, politics, nonfiction, criminal records, discrimination, bias, hiring practices, job applications, masculinity, men, milwaukee, urban, city, african americans, ex convicts.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226644851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226644851/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles